#Plot for Uni-variate  analysis:
def plot_distribution(data):
    f,(ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw= {"height_ratios": (0.2, 1)})
    mean, median, mode = data.mean(), data.median(), data.mode().get_values()[0]
    
    sns.boxplot(data, ax=ax_box)
    ax_box.axvline(mean, color='r', linestyle='--')
    ax_box.axvline(median, color='g', linestyle='-')
    ax_box.axvline(mode, color='b', linestyle='-')

    sns.distplot(data,rug=True,ax=ax_hist)
    ax_hist.axvline(mean, color='r', linestyle='--')
    ax_hist.axvline(median, color='g', linestyle='-')
    ax_hist.axvline(mode, color='b', linestyle='-')
    plt.legend({'Mean':mean,'Median':median,'Mode':mode})

Uni-variate Analysis: Outliers are reprsented on corresponding boxplots. Histogram shows the distribution of each attribute along with its central values.

Cement: This column defines how much Kg of Cement is mixed in the concrete mixture. There are no missing values, the Mean(281) and 50% percentile-Median (273) are almost same. The difference between min value and first quartile is 90, however the difference bwn third quartile and max is high(190), so the distribution should have longer tail on the right side of the curve.

In [7]:
plot_distribution(concrete_df['cement'])

Slag: Blast Furnace Slag is nonmetallic coproduct produced in the process of production of Iron. There are 471 values populated as zeros (0s). There could be chances that on these scenarios Slag might not be mixed in concrete so it is represented as 0 or else these are missing values? Min and first quartile values are 0 and there is huge difference(216.45) between 3rd quartile and max value. So there could be long tail in the right side of the distribution. Mean is 74 and median is 22, hence the distribution is not centred.

ash: Fly Ash is being used as replacement of Cement in the concrete to a certain extent. There are no missing values, but 232 zeros present, which means on these scenarios ash is not mixed on the concrete. Here again the min and 1st quartile values are zero, there is a difference of 80 for 3rd quartile and max value. Again a tail in the right side of the distribution. Median is 0 and mean is 54.

There are lot of concrete mixtures kept for very less days, very minimal studies made with longer age (since keeping it for longer days takes time for assessment, hence more studies would have been performed with lesser days). During bi-variate analysis we can see the relation between the age & strength if there is any contribution in keeping it for longer duration. def getMonth(age):
    for month in range(1,12):
        if(age <= 30*month and age > 30*(month-1)):
            return month
    return 12

#Reusable method for adding result score
def addRow(df,ls):
    numEl = len(ls)
    newRow = pd.DataFrame(np.array(ls).reshape(1,numEl), columns = list(df.columns))
    df = df.append(newRow, ignore_index=True)
    return df
In [28]:
#Reusable method to perform regressionMOdelling
def regressionModel(model, X,y,df):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=.30, random_state=0)    
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_predict = model.predict(X_test)
    score = model.score(X_test, y_test)
    RMSE = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_predict))
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_predict)
    df = addRow(df,[model.__class__.__name__, score, RMSE,r2])
    return df

#Trying various models
def doModelling(X,y):
    output_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = op_columns)
    model = LinearRegression()
    output_df = regressionModel(model,X,y,output_df)
    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree = 2) 
    X_poly = poly.fit_transform(X) 
    output_df = regressionModel(model,X_poly,y,output_df)
    model = Lasso()
    output_df = regressionModel(model,X_poly,y,output_df)
    model = Ridge()
    output_df = regressionModel(model,X_poly,y,output_df)
    model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=50)
    output_df = regressionModel(model,X_poly,y,output_df)
    model = GradientBoostingRegressor()
    output_df = regressionModel(model,X_poly,y,output_df)
    model = AdaBoostRegressor()
    output_df = regressionModel(model,X_poly,y,output_df)
    X_Z = X.apply(zscore)
    model = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors= 3, weights = 'distance')
    output_df = regressionModel(model,X_Z,y,output_df)
    model = DecisionTreeRegressor()
    output_df = regressionModel(model,X_poly,y,output_df)
    model = XGBRegressor(objective ='reg:squarederror')
    output_df = regressionModel(model,X,y,output_df)
    xgboost.plot_importance(model)
    return output_df

#K-Fold Cross Validation
def performKFold(model):
    kfold = KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=0)
    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree = 2) 
    X_poly = poly.fit_transform(X) 
    res = cross_val_score(model, X_poly, y, cv=kfold)
    print("Model: ",model.__class__.__name__, "Score Mean: ",res.mean()*100.0, "Score Std: ", res.std()*100.0)

In [40]:
#Finding 95% confidence level through Bootstraping
n_iterations = 100           # Number of bootstrap samples to create (Since the machine is slow ran for 100 times, otherwise ideal to run for around 1000 times)
n_size = int(len(concrete_filtered) * 0.50)    # picking only 50 % of the given data in every bootstrap sample
# run bootstrap
stats = list()
values = concrete_filtered.values
for i in range(n_iterations):
	# prepare train and test sets
	train = resample(values, n_samples=n_size)  # Sampling with replacement 
	test = np.array([x for x in values if x.tolist() not in train.tolist()])  # picking rest of the data not considered in sample
    # fit model
	model = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=params['n_estimators'], learning_rate=params['learning_rate']) # Model based on Hyper param tuning
	model.fit(train[:,:-1], train[:,-1])
    # evaluate model
	predictions = model.predict(test[:,:-1])
	score = r2_score(test[:,-1], predictions)    
	stats.append(score)

alpha = 0.95                             # for 95% confidence 
p = ((1.0-alpha)/2.0) * 100              # tail regions on right and left .25 on each side indicated by P value (border)
lower = max(0.0, np.percentile(stats, p))  
p = (alpha+((1.0-alpha)/2.0)) * 100
upper = min(1.0, np.percentile(stats, p))
print('%.1f confidence interval %.1f%% and %.1f%%' % (alpha*100, lower*100, upper*100))

95.0 confidence interval 85.5% and 91.1%

Conclusion: GrandientBoostingRegressor Algorithm works best for the given dataset. Model Score is 85.5% and 91.1% at the 95% confidence Level.
